[5] India, Gujarat, canine, bovine, human exposure
Date: Sat 2 Jul 2016, 6.45 AM IST Source: The Times of India [edited]
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/surat/Rabid-dog-attacks-cattle-six-people-in-Valsad-village/articleshowprint/53016248.cms?null

Residents of Panchlai village in Valsad's Pardi taluka woke up to a fierce attack by a rabid dog on Thu [30 Jun 2016] night. The dog attacked 6 people, including 2 women, and over a dozen cattle.

Stray dog menace in the village of Valsad and nearby areas is assuming serious proportions. The incident occurred at Dipli Falia in Panchlai village at midnight. The victims were sleeping outside their houses when the dog attacked them. Before attacking the villagers, the dog had bitten the cattle heads that were tied. Locals said the canine had come into the area only a few days ago and had been attacking other dogs too. "The dog started biting people around 11pm in Dipli Faliya. People tried to stone the dog which only made it more aggressive," said Harshad Patel, an eyewitness and relative of a victim.

The victims were immediately rushed to a private hospital at Dharampur, some 15 km [approx. 9 mi]from the village. The victims were administered anti-rabies vaccination and allowed to go home.

A victim, K.P., 60, said, "I was sleeping outside the house at night when the dog came near me. I woke up and the dog bit on my hand. When I screamed, it left the spot and attacked another woman sleeping next to my house."

Village elder Bacchubhai Patel said, "We tried to locate the dog at night, but could not find it in the dark. So, we started the hunt in the morning and found the dog on the outskirts of the village. We ghearoed the dog and killed it. Patel added, "The rabid dog has bitten other dogs in the village. We fear that the victim dogs may also contract rabies. Thus, we have asked the village panchayat to catch the dogs and release them in the jungle."

--
