[6] India, Pune, Marharastra, fatal human case
Date: Mon 4 Jul 2016, 12.57 AM IST
Source: The Times of India [edited]
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/pune/Kondhwa-woman-succumbs-to-rabies/articleshowprint/53037093.cms?null

A 40-year-old woman died of rabies at the municipal corporation run Naidu Infectious Diseases Hospital on 1 Jul 2016. The deceased, identified as K.K., was a resident of Vidyanagar on Katraj-Kondhwa Road. She was brought to the hospital on 30 Jun 2016, doctors said, adding that she was already in a critical condition by then.

With this, the number of deaths due to the fatal infection has risen to 14 this year. This is, however, the 1st rabies casualty reported among city residents, as the rest were referred to Pune hospitals from nearby areas.

K.K. developed symptoms like fever, pain in abdomen, sweating and breathlessness a few days ago and was admitted to a private hospital. After her condition worsened, she was shifted to Naidu Hospital around 8.20pm on 30 June. "She had full-blown rabies symptoms at the time of admission; she had already developed a fear of water and air. Her condition was critical," the doctor said.

A civic health official said, "It was a category-III dog bite wound. As per her medical history, she did not take any anti-rabies vaccination or fast-acting antibodies on the scheduled days. She was also not given rabies immunoglobulin, a ready-made antibody which is extremely effective in deactivating the virus in a category-III dog-bite injury."

The victims are usually injected with a fast-acting ready-made antibody and rabies immunoglobulin (RIG) near the wound to deactivate the rabies virus. The antibodies are given to the patient for immediate protection because the vaccine generally takes 14 days to produce antibodies.

As per World Health Organisation (WHO) guidelines, RIG should be given for all category-III exposed patients, irrespective of the interval between the exposure and the beginning of the treatment.

